message: One of the most significant religious festivals of #Kerala, Pongala is celebrated at the famous Attukal Bhagavathi Temple in Thiruvananthapuram. The festival, celebrated with a lot of enthusiasm and fervour, has found its place in the Guinness records as the largest congregation of women in the state for a religious activity. Only women are allowed to take part in the sacred Pongala ritual. The Pongala - a sweet dish prepared with rice porridge, sweet brown molasses, coconut gratings, nuts and raisins - is offered by the devotees to the presiding deity of the temple, Goddess Attukalamma, in a bid to appease her. The event witnesses a massive influx of devotees annually while the whole city gets decked in festive splendour.

Keibul Lamjao, situated in Manipur, is the only 'floating' sanctuary in the world. It mainly consists of 40 sq. km. of wetland with 1.5 m. deep floating vegetation. The park is also known for its rare and unique fauna and is home to the Sangai or brow-antlered deer, one of the most endangered species of deer in the world.

With its forested hills, tranquil beaches and the Chikoo orchards, Dahanu is a place of great picturesque charm. Every year a two-day Chikoo Festival is organized in Dahanu, Maharashtra. The festival features local dancers, workshops, food stalls, farm visits and much more.

#Dahanu #Maharashtra #Chikoo #IncredibleIndia

message:
Constructed in 1848 AD, the Hutheesing Jain Temple in Ahmedabad is an outstanding specimen of Jain architecture and is dedicated to Dharamnath, the 15th Tirthankara of Jains. The temple complex comprises a huge dome, porches projecting on three sides with beautifully decorated columns and figural bracket, exquisitely paved courtyards and arcades that enclose 52 shrines. 

#Spiritual #architecture #Jainism #Ahmedabad #Gujarat #IncredibleIndia

message:
Ranakpur, a quaint village situated in the Aravalli mountain ranges in the Pali district of Rajasthan, is home to one of the biggest and most significant Jain temple complexes in India. 

The temple comprises 29 halls, 80 domes and 1444 unique marble pillars, each of them intricately carved, yet no two are alike.The main temple, the Adinath or Chaumukha temple (the four-faced temple), is dedicated to the first Tirthankara, Adinath.

#Jainism #Pali #Rajasthan #IncredibleIndia
name: Timeline Photos
story: Incredible India with Rajasthan Tourism at RanakPur Temple.

Vivekananda Rock Memorial, located in Vavathurai, Kanyakumari, India, was built in 1970 in honour of the great Indian spiritual leader and reformer, Swami Vivekananda.

Established in 1958, the Namgyal Institute of Tibetology (NIT), located in Gangtok, #Sikkim, is a significant reference centre in Buddhist studies. The institute also consists of a museum, a Tibetan library and a reference centre on Tibet and the Himalayas.

The Namgyal Institute of Tibetology is a fabulous treasure trove of Tibetan literature and artefacts, the only one of its kind in India and one among the three in the whole world.

message: Ziro Valley is one of the most strikingly picturesque landscapes in India. Situated in the Lower Subansiri District of Arunachal Pradesh, Ziro Valley is known for its amazing natural beauty. The region has a vast expanse of rice fields and is surrounded by mountains that have plenty of pine trees. Besides, Ziro Valley is also home to quaint little villages of the Apatani tribes who dwell in this region.

message:
Held annually in December in the backdrop of the famous Sun temple in Konark, Odisha, the Konark dance festival is an incredible visual feast for dance lovers. 

The festival showcases various dance forms including Odissi, Bharatanatyam, Manipuri, Kathak and Chau. Besides, there is a handicrafts mela and food stalls offering a wide range of delicious cuisine. 

The festival is an excellent platform for performing artists as well as dance connoisseurs.

message:
The City Palace Museum, the main part of the City Palace in Udaipur, #Rajasthan, comprises several palaces and houses a fascinating collection of rare murals, ancient sculptures, glass inlay work, and personal possessions of some of the rulers. 

A noticeable aspect of the museum is its surreal chess floor - a beautiful tribute to the origins and history of Chess. ‘Chaturanga’, which developed around the 6th century AD, in India is believed to be the ancestor of various board games including chess and was a favourite pastime of Indian royalty.

The earliest diamonds were discovered in India in the 4th century BC. In fact, diamonds were first mined centuries ago in India, where significant amounts of alluvial deposits of the stone were found along the Penner, the Krishna, and the Godavari rivers.

A majority of the early stones were transported along the network of trade routes that linked India and China, commonly called the Silk Road.

message:
The Pushkar camel fair is a cultural, trade and religious fair held in the quaint town of Pushkar, 11 km from Ajmer, for 12 days every year. This year, the fair would be held from 8-14 November.

It is a lively and fascinating spectacle with Rajasthani men and women in exuberant traditional attire; sadhus in saffron robes, smeared with ash; and thousands of  cows, sheep, goats, bulls, horses and camels in beautifully decorated saddles. Pushkar camel fair, the largest camel fair in the world, attracts more than 1,00,000 people, from across the country and abroad.

Besides the religious rituals and trading, people take part in various cultural and sporting events.

The construction of the temple is believed to have begun in the 11th century during the reign of the Paramara king, Bhoja. The site received the National Tourism Award (2013–14) for the "Best maintained and Disabled Friendly Monument” in 2015.

message:
Sanchi, situated about 40 kms from Bhopal, Madhya Pradesh, is well-known for its specimens of Buddhist art and architecture, belonging to the period between the third century BC and the twelfth century AD. Sanchi Stupa, the most famous of all the Sanchi monuments, was commissioned by Emperor Ashoka. Stupas are massive hemispherical domes, comprising a central chamber, in which the relics of the Buddha have been kept. The ancient Stupas, monasteries, temples, and monolithic pillars are an excellent testimony to Buddhist art. 

Today, this magnificent monument is accessible to the differently-abled. With a tactile walkway for the visually impaired, information plaques in Braille, Braille maps, and a pathway that can be accessed by wheelchair, the monument ensures easy, barrier-free access for all.

Samantha Gash, an endurance athlete from Melbourne and a strong advocate for social change, is running across #India to raise funds for education of underprivileged children in India, Samantha will cover nearly 3,800 km from Jaisalmer in #Rajasthan to Mawsynram in #Meghalaya within a period of 76 days. A corporate speaker, writer  & social entrepreneur, Samantha is also the first woman and the youngest person ever to complete the ‘4 Deserts Grand Slam’, one of the toughest endurance events on the planet.

message:
The Albert Hall Museum or the Government Central Museum is the oldest museum in #Rajasthan. Designed in 1876 by Colonel Sir Swinton Jacob, the building was constructed for welcoming King Edward VII, the Prince of Wales, on his visit to India. 

Situated amidst the beautiful gardens of Ram Niwas Bagh in Jaipur, the museum has an exquisite collection of rare articles including carpets, textiles, paintings, metal and wood crafts, pottery, arms and weapons, toys, dolls and even an Egyptian mummy from the Ptolemaic Epoch. 

The museum was opened for public in 1886. With its magnificent archways, courtyards, and towers, the museum stands testimony to the rich architectural heritage of the country. Needless to say, the museum offers a splendid visual feast for tourists and history connoisseurs.

message:
Karva Chauth is a popular festival celebrated by married Hindu women in the Western and  Northern parts of India, especially in Punjab, Rajasthan, Haryana, Gujarat and Uttar Pradesh. During this festival, all married Hindu women observe a fasting ritual seeking the prosperity. longevity and well-being of their husbands. The fast is observed for a whole day, starting from early morning till late evening or late night. 

This festival falls 9 days prior to Diwali, on the fourth day of the new moon soon after Dusshera, in the month of 'Karthik' (October-November).

message:
The Sambhar Lake, located in #Rajasthan, is the largest saline lake in India. The lake, popularly known as the ‘Gift from Thar desert’, is mentioned in the mythological epic, ‘Mahabharata'. It produces 2,10,000 tonnes of salt annually, making it one among the three leading salt-producing states in India. The 5.1 km long sandstone dam, which divides the lake basin, helps in salt production. 

The Salt laboratory and the Salt museum are really worth a visit.

message:
The Rashtrapati Niwas or Viceregal Lodge, situated on the Observatory Hills of #Shimla, Himachal Pradesh, was originally the residence of Lord Dufferin, the British Viceroy of India (1884-1888). 

The building was designed in the Jacobethan style of architecture. Later it also served as the summer retreat of the President of India. In fact, in the early 60’s, the President of India, Dr. S. Radhakrishnan, and the Prime Minister, Jawaharlal Nehru, made it a scholars’ abode. The Indian Institute of Advanced Study (IIAS), a research institute, shifted into the lodge in 1965.

The museum located inside the institution houses some of the ancient photographs and texts that date to the British colonial rule.

message:
Double-hump camels, found in #Ladakh, is a major attraction for domestic as well as international tourists. While the one-hump camel is found in hot deserts, the double-hump camels are inhabitants of cold-desert regions. Since centuries, the double-hump Bactrian camels have been a significant mode of transportation in Ladakh.
Take an exciting two-hour Camel safari in Nubra Valley, from Hundar Village to Diskit, the capital town of Nubra, and enjoy the scenic charm of the landscape. The best time to take the safari is from July to September.
name: Timeline Photos

message:
The Kutch Bustard Sanctuary, situated in the Naliya region of Kutch district, #Gujarat, was primarily established to save the Great Indian bustard from poaching and hunting. The Kutch Bustard Sanctuary is essentially a grassland area dotted with dry grasslands and desert vegetation. The sanctuary is regarded as a unique habitat for the Great Indian bustard which is almost on the verge of extinction in some of the regions of India. The Great Indian Bustard is a ground-dwelling bird with a long neck and elongated legs. While Florican Bustards breed in the region, the vibrant Macqueen’s Bustard is a winter visitor. 

Some of the rare species of animals and birds that inhabit the sanctuary include Chinkaras, Jungle cats, Nilgai, Indian Wolf and various other mammals.
name: Timeline Photos

message:
Dussehra or #Vijayadashmi, is a popular Hindu festival that is celebrated on the tenth day of Ashvin month as per the Hindu calendar in the month of September or October. Navratri is celebrated for the first nine days, culminating with Dussehra on the tenth day. The day commemorates the killing of demon king Ravana by Lord Rama and also marks the triumph of Goddess Durga over the demon Mahishasura, thus symbolizing the victory of good over evil. During Dussehra, special prayer meetings and food offerings to the gods are held in temples throughout the country. Effigies of demon king Ravana are burnt on bonfires in the evening. In West Bengal, huge idols of Goddess Durga are immersed in the waters of river Ganga. 

#IncredibleIndia wishes everyone a fun-filled and colourful #Dussehra

Drenched in sunlight, the temples along the banks of the Ganges River, the old buildings, ashrams and palaces look completely surreal.

message:
The city of #Mysore is at its best during the 10-day Dussehra festival. The Dussehra celebrations have a vibrant history and a tradition of more than 400 years that could be traced to the Vijayanagar kings in the 15th century. The Mysore Dasara festival begins with a dazzling procession of decorated elephants led by the Maharaja of Mysore.

The majestic Maharaja’s Palace is beautifully illuminated by nearly 100,000 light bulbs every evening. The entire town gets a makeover, with fabulous dance performances, concerts, sporting demonstrations and various cultural events. On the Vijayadashami day, the festivities conclude with a torchlight parade.
name: Timeline Photos

message:
Located in #Karnataka, the Bandipur National Park is a favourite destination for wildlife enthusiasts and nature lovers. One of the most popular wildlife sanctuaries in the country, Bandipur National Park spans an area of 874 sq. km. and is a treasure house of flora and fauna. The Park  is home to a substantially large population of Asiatic elephants and Indian tigers. The floral vegetation mainly comprises the deciduous and evergreen forests and the moist and grassy woodlands. Discover diverse species of flora, fauna and avifauna in the company of an experienced guide.

So head to Bandipur Park, and get ready for a fascinating wildlife tour.

message:
Durga Puja is one of the most popular festivals celebrated in West Bengal, especially in #Kolkata. 

The 10-day festival is celebrated in honour of Goddess Durga during Navaratri. Beginning from the sixth day till the ninth day, elaborate pandals with beautiful, life-size idols of Goddess Durga are open for visitors. The tenth day or Dashami marks the immersion of the idol in water with magnificent processions. People of Bengal celebrate this festival in the last four days of Navratri. 

During the festival, you will find Bengali girls and women dressed in exquisite saris and men in kurta-pyjama. Maha aarti is performed every evening. Devotees perform the Dhunuchi dance to the rhythmic beats of Dhak. The sounds of Dhak, Dhunuchi nach and the subtle fragrance of Shiuli adds to the spirit of the celebrations.

message:
Dandiya Raas is the traditional folk dance form of #Gujarat. It is also the special dance performed during Navaratri in Western India. 

This dance form originated as devotional Garba dance performed in honour of Goddess Durga. Nicknamed ‘The Sword Dance’, Dandiya Raas actually represents the mock-fight between Goddess Durga and Mahishasura, the powerful demon-king. Dandiya Raas involves men and women dancing in circular movements, with sticks in their hands. The sticks of the dance symbolize the sword of Goddess Durga. The men wear special turbans and kedias, while women wear colourful and vibrant traditional dresses such as ghagra, embroidered choli and bandhani dupattas sparkling with mirror work and heavy jewellery. 

The dance is associated with Holi & the Raaslila of Radha and Krishna at Vrindavan.

message: #Bodhgaya or Uruvela, as it was known during Buddha’s times, is also a major pilgrimage centre for Hindus as Buddha is considered to be the ninth incarnation of Vishnu.#BuddhistConclave2016 #Buddhism #Bihar

The magnificent Hoysala architecture developed and flourished under the reign of the Hoysala rulers between the 11th and 14th centuries. During their rule, the Hoysalas constructed more than 1500 small and big temples across the empire of which only a few survive today. 

Some of the outstanding specimens of Hoysala architectural style include the Chennakesava Temple at #Belur, the Hoysaleswara Temple at Halebidu, and the Kesava Temple at Somanathapura. A unique feature of Hoysala architecture is the use of soft soapstone for building the structures; soapstone was widely used as it was much more suitable for intricate carvings. 

The Mahalaxmi Devi temple in the Hassan District of 
#Karnataka, built by the Hoysala King Vishnuvardhana in 11th century AD, is built in soapstone and is elaborately carved.

message:
The Dal Lake is one of the most popular lakes in #Srinagar and is home to exquisitely carved wooden houseboats, splendid shikaras and floating gardens. The lake is surrounded by the snow-covered Pir Panjal mountain range, situated at a height of 5,425 metres. Dal Lake, popularly known as the "Jewel in the crown of Kashmir,” is also a significant source for fishing and water plant harvesting. The lake is also notable for its beautiful lotus flowers which bloom in July and August. 

The sunrise and sunset at Dal lake is a spectacular sight; soaked in golden light, the lake appears absolutely ethereal. Viewing the sunset over the Dal lake should be a must-do on your itinerary if you are a photography enthusiast or a nature lover.

Gandhi Jayanti is celebrated in India every year on 2nd October to mark the occasion of the birthday of Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi, the "Father of the Nation". During Gandhi Jayanti, prayer services and tributes are held across India, particularly at Raj Ghat, Gandhiji's memorial in New Delhi. Prayer meetings and commemorative ceremonies are also organized in colleges, government institutions, and socio-political institutions on this occasion.

Let us follow the path of truth and non-violence and salute the Father of the nation on this day.

message:
Organic honey is procured from the wild forests usually by tribals. The honey is extracted directly from bee hives. Dark in colour with higher mineral content, forest honey is believed to possess numerous health benefits. It helps to boost immunity, aids weight loss, smoothens the skin, prevents cancer, and has various healing properties. 100% pure and natural honey is a fabulous addition to breads and can be used as toppings on waffles or mixed with cold coffee.

Buy a jar of this sweet potion when you are at Thenmala, a forest region in #Kerala popular for high-quality honey.

message:
A mammal usually found in the Eastern Himalayas and Southwestern China, the Red Panda is a little larger than a domestic cat with reddish-brown fur, a long, shaggy tail, bear-like body and waddling gait. 

Red Pandas are extremely acrobatic and feeds mainly on bamboos. They are basically solitary animals and are generally active from dusk to dawn. These animals use their bushy tails for balance and to protect themselves in winter. 

Red Panda is the State animal of #Sikkim. The International Union for Conservation of Nature ( IUCN) has classified the Red Panda as Endangered Species.

message:
Spread across a sprawling area of 940 sq.km, Kanha National Park is one of the largest parks in Madhya Pradesh. 

A popular tiger reserve, the Park hosts a significant population of the majestic royal Bengal tigers. In 1879, Kanha National Park was declared a reserve forest. One of the greatest wildlife reserves in the country, Kanha National Park hosts a variety of wild animals, from  leopards, tigers and wild dogs to innumerable species of birds, plants, reptiles and insects. 

The picturesque landscape, the beautiful meadows, crystal clear streams and the thick forests offer an incredible visual treat for nature lovers. And what’s more, this beautiful, vibrant landscape has been the source of inspiration for Rudyard Kipling’s "The Jungle Book".

Though it seems to be an arduous task, if you can walk for a few hours without much difficulty and strain, you can make it.

message:
The #Sundarbans, situated at the mouth of the Ganges river, is the largest river delta in the world and the largest estuarine mangrove forest in the world. A UNESCO World Heritage site, the Sundarbans encompasses an area of 4624 sq. km in India, and is home to a wide range of bird, reptile and invertebrate species. A national park, a tiger reserve and a biosphere reserve in India; the Sunderbans provides habitat to various species of crabs, fishes, shrimps and fauna. 

Visit this wildlife haven anytime from October to March for an awesome tryst with the wild.

message:
Nalanda was a renowned Mahavihara or a large Buddhist monastery in the ancient kingdom of Magadha, and one of the oldest universities in the world. The construction of the university started in 5th century AD in the Gupta period. 

The Nalanda site, located about 98 kilometres from #Patna, includes the archaeological remnants dating from the 3rd century BC to the 13th century AD. It comprises stupas, shrines, viharas and significant artworks in stucco, stone, and metal.

The ruins of ancient Nalanda Mahavihara have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

Hill Forts of Rajasthan - This UNESCO heritage site comprises six majestic forts; Chittorgarh, Kumbhalgarh, Sawai Madhopur, Jhalawar, Jaipur and Jaisalmer.

The amazing architecture of the forts, some of them up to 20 kilometres in circumference, bears witness to the might and grandeur of the Rajput princely states that flourished from the 8th to the 18th centuries. Enclosed within the fortifications are some of the prominent urban centres, palaces, trading centres and temples - an eloquent testimony to a courtly culture that patronised learning, music and the arts.

Explore this amazing site on your trip to #Rajasthan.

The massive rock at Chadayamangalam, #Kerala, derives its name from the mythical bird Jatayu in the epic Ramayana. The bird is believed to have fallen on the rock after he failed in his efforts to prevent the kidnapping of Sita by Ravana. 

A nature park project named Jatayu Nature Park has been started with the objective of promoting adventure, mythology and wellness tourism. The park covers over 65 acres of land and hosts a giant sculpture of Jatayu. Regarded as the world’s largest bird sculpture, it will house a 6D theatre and an audio-visual based digital museum that will give the visitors interesting glimpses of the Ramayana. 

This enchanting sculpture will surely woo the world.

message:
Puri, a beautiful coastal town in the state of #Odisha, attracts a large number of tourists every year from across the globe. Puri is popularly known for the Shri Jagannath Temple, Puri Beach and the Konark Sun Temple, the UNESCO World Heritage Site. 

Jagannatha Temple is one of the four most sacred places in India. The temple is dedicated to Lord Krishna or Jagannath and has three main deities namely; Lord Jagannatha, Goddess Subhadra and Lord Balabhadra. According to legends, Puri is the birthplace of Lord Vishwakarma. It is believed that Lord Vishwakarma and Lord Vishnu (disguised as a carpenter) had helped to construct the temple.

If you are an architectural connoisseur or want to learn more about the splendid heritage of Odisha, Puri is the best place to be in.

message:
Onam, the harvest festival of #Kerala, is celebrated with much gaiety and fervour irrespective of caste, creed or religion. The week-long festivities mainly involve Onasadhya (traditional feast), intricately decorated Pookalam (flower carpet) ,Thiruvathira (a traditional dance form),Vallamkali (boat race) and various traditional games and art forms.

The ten-day festival falls during the Malayalam month of Chingam, between August & September, and marks the homecoming of the legendary, righteous king Mahabali.

message:
Located in Thanesar, 7 kms from #Kurukshetra; the place synonymous with Mahabharata, Sheikh Chehli’s tomb is a memorial built as a tribute to Sheikh Chehli, a renowned scholar and teacher to Dara Shikoh, eldest son of the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan.

 The complex comprises two tombs, a madrasa, a splendid garden and an archaeological museum. The second tomb is dedicated to Sheikh Chilli's wife. The marble tomb of Sheikh Chehli contains his mortal remains and is an excellent specimen of Mughal architecture with a unique persian flavour. 

The massive domes, large halls, arched gateways and ornate embellishment make this monument a true visual delight, comparable to the Taj in architectural style and splendour.

message:
A popular hill station, #Darjeeling is a much-loved destination for tea exploration in the country. Popularly known for its lush tea gardens, estates, vintage bungalows and tea factories, Darjeeling offers you an incredible opportunity to learn about tea tasting as well. Tea tasting is a very refined art; one that requires a lot of training, dedication & experience. It is done by professional tea tasters to determine the quality and flavour of tea leaves. 

A good taster should have a well-trained palate, prodigious memory, alert senses and the aptitude to constantly compare, classify, and draw on previous experiences to evaluate a particular type of tea within seconds. A tea taster understands and appreciates the subtle nuances - the flavours, aroma and colours - between different types of tea and helps you discover your favourite.

message: Crush, tear, curl (CTC) is a method used for processing black tea. In this method, leaves are placed through a series of cylindrical rollers with sharp teeth, which crush, tear and curl the tea leaves into small, hard pellets. The tea processed using the CTC method brews faster and yields more cups of tea per kilogram. The brewed tea often has a rich reddish-brown color, such as the #Nilgiri tea.

message:
Want to add a dash of royalty & splendour on your wedding day? Look no further; #Rajasthan, India’s royal state known for its exquisite havelis and royal palaces, is just the right place for a grand, luxurious wedding. Udaipur, known as Venice of the East, is one of the most popular wedding destinations in Rajasthan, thanks to its splendid lakes, magnificent palaces and romantic ambience.

Tie the knot at any of the fascinating wedding venues, such as Devi Garh, an 18th century fort and palace, or the City Palace Complex, where the royal family of Mewar still resides. Jaipur, the Pink City, is another exciting wedding destination; here you can choose from a plenty of venues including the Jal Mahal Palace or the Samode Palace. Jodhpur, the Blue City, offers you a world of opulence, luxury and grandeur - go in for the spectacular Umaid Bhavan Palace, or the regal Mehrangarh Fort. 

Rajasthan has always remained a favourite with celebrities - Katy Perry, Madonna and Elizabeth Hurley have tied the knot in this splendid state.

message: Ganesh Chaturthi is a Hindu festival celebrated to honour the birth of the elephant-headed God in Hindu mythology, Ganesha. The ten-day festival is celebrated with great fervour across India. Pandals (tents) are set up, houses are cleaned, and delicious sweets are prepared on the occasion. A ritual called Pranapratishhtha, which involves chanting of mantras by the priest, is performed. Clay idols of Lord Ganesha in various shapes and sizes are brought and placed in homes and pandals. Special Ganpati prayers, songs and devotional chanting are also part of the occasion.In Maharashtra, people purchase clay or metal idols of Lord Ganesha and worship them for one to ten days. The deities are then taken out in a majestic procession through the streets and immersed in a river, well or sea.

Get hitched at the Havelock Islands or the Ross Islands, the perfect destinations for a beach wedding. Apart from the marriage ceremony, it will be an absolutely wonderful holiday experience for the guests too. 

So, head to the beautiful Andamans and make your marriage a truly unforgettable one!

Your wedding is one of the most significant moments in your life. In India, destination wedding is a trend which is fast catching on these days. If you are on the hunt for an exotic wedding destination, India offers a treasure trove of options - forts, palaces, beaches, vineyards & lots more.

message:
Jaipur, the capital of #Rajasthan, is an epitome of royalty and magnificence. Jaipur is famously known as the ‘Pink City’ because of the colour of the stone used in the construction of the city. Besides its oriental charm, the city is popular for its exquisite handicraft items, embroidered apparel, and splendid culture and history. If Jaipur leaves you awestruck with its fairy tale charm, Jodhpur enthralls you with its pretty blue visage. Jodhpur, the ‘Blue City’, is a true architectural marvel. 

Stroll through the narrow lanes lined with Jodhpur’s blue houses and immerse yourself in a spellbinding, out-of-the-world experience.
name: Timeline Photos

message: One of the major festivals in India, Holi celebrates the victory of good over evil and the arrival of spring and harvest season. The festival is celebrated with much gaiety and enthusiasm on the full moon day in March as per the Gregorian calendar. Holi is a festival of colours - Men, women, and children throw and smear brightly coloured powders and liquid colours on the clothes and faces of neighbours and relatives. Each colour has special relevance, and the brightest colours - blue, yellow, red, purple, pink and green - are the most popular ones.

message:
The Taj Mahal in #Agra is one of the most recognisable and iconic monuments in the world. Constructed between 1631 and 1653, the mausoleum is a spectacular combination of Hindu, Islamic and Persian styles of architecture. It took 22 years and 20,000 workers to complete this architectural wonder. In addition to its rich history and stunning architecture, there are numerous interesting facts associated with the Taj Mahal. 

Do you know that the Taj Mahal takes on different hues at different times of the day - pinkish in the morning, milky white in the evening, and golden under the moonlit skies?  It is believed that the changing colour of the Taj signifies the fluctuating moods of women, particularly the queen, Mumtaz Mahal.

message: Peacock, the National bird of India, has been a symbol of majestic grace, elegance, royalty and rebirth since the primitive times. With its flamboyant hues, fan-shaped crest of feathers, a long, slender neck, and glittering blue breast, the male species of the bird appears strikingly enticing than its female counterpart. The courtship dance of the male, spreading out its tail and preening its exquisite feathers, is a fascinating sight. If you are an avid peacock lover, do visit the Bankapura peacock sanctuary in #Karnataka, the only second sanctuary in the country that is exclusively involved in the conservation and breeding of peacocks.

message: The cuisine of #Goa is a fascinating reflection of its history and heritage. The cuisine is mainly influenced by its Hindu origins, Portuguese colonialism, and some innovative techniques. Fish, coconut milk, rice, and local spices are the major components of Goan cuisine. Goan cuisine is basically characterized by the intense use of spices and flavours and use of kokum.  The most common delicacy is Kingfish (Vison or Viswan), Pomfret, Shark, Tuna and Mackerel, Crabs, Prawns, Tiger Prawns, Lobster, Squid, and Mussels.

message: Usgalimal in South #Goa is known for its prehistoric petroglyphs (rock art). Spanning an area of 500 sq.m on the banks of the Kushavati River, these engravings date back to 20,000 or 30,000 years. The petroglyphs are carved on the laterite-stone ground and depict numerous scenes including bulls, deer and antelope, a dancing woman, a peacock and ‘triskelions’ (a series of concentric circles believed to be an ancient method of measuring time). These carvings are assumed to be the work of one of Goa’s primitive tribes, the Kush, and were discovered by archaeologists in 1993.

message: Narcondam is an extremely remote volcanic island located in the Andaman sea. A part of the #Andaman islands, the thickly vegetated #Narcondam is home to around 300 Narcondam hornbills, a species endemic to this small island. Encompassing an area of approximately 6.8 square kilometres,  the island is almost completely uninhabited except for a small police outpost. Narcondam Island's 710 meters high volcanic mountain is the second tallest point in the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.

message: The #Aga Khan Palace or the Gandhi National Museum in Pune is a monument of great historical significance. The palace occupies an important place in the history of India’s freedom struggle; it acted as a prison for national leaders including #Mahatma Gandhi during the Quit India Movement in 1942. Built by Sultan Mohammed Shah Aga Khan III in 1892, the museum serves as a memorial wherein the remains of Kasturba Gandhi, Mahatma Gandhi’s wife, are kept. A beautiful combination of Islamic and Italian architecture, the palace has five halls and spacious verandahs, and also comprises a gallery which has some of the belongings of #Gandhiji.

message: The Cellular Jail or Kala-Pani in Andaman and Nicobar Islands is a political prison in the Andaman & Nicobar Islands where the British used to exile political prisoners. Several prominent freedom fighters and Indian activists, including Batukeshwar Dutt and Veer Savarkar, were imprisoned in Cellular jail during India’s Independence struggle. The construction of the jail started in 1896 and was completed in 1906. Initially, there were seven wings comprising 698 cells radiating from a central tower. Today, the first floor of the building houses an Art Gallery, Netaji Gallery, and a Library on Freedom Movement. A Gallery on the First War of Independence and another on Old Photographs have been established in the premises of the National Memorial.

message: Amar Jawan Jyothi or Flame of the Immortal Soldier holds a prominent place in the history of #India. Located below the famous arch of India Gate, the Amar Jawan Jyothi is built in honour of the unknown soldiers who lost their lives during the 1971 Indo-Pak war. It is designed as a black marble cenotaph with a rifle positioned on the barrel. The cenotaph is placed on an edifice with four torches perpetually kept alive in its four corners. Indira Gandhi inaugurated the structure in 1972. Today, the Amar Jawan Jyothi is visited by the President and Prime Minister annually during state occasions.

message: The #Red Fort or Lal Qila was commissioned by Emperor Shah Jahan in 1639. Built on the banks of the River Yamuna, it took nine years to construct the fort. One of the massive forts in India and a #UNESCO World heritage site, the Red Fort was the seat of Mughal power up to 1857 and is a testimony to the power and splendour of the great Mughals. Some of the prominent attractions of the fort are the Diwan-i-Am (the hall of public audiences), Diwan-i-khas (the hall of private audiences), Royal bath, the Shahi Burj and the Moti Masjid built by Aurangazeb for his private use. The Prime Minister of India makes his Independence Day speech on August 15 from the ramparts of Red Fort.

message: The #Hodka village, situated at the edge of Gujarat’s Rann of Kutch, was inhabited about 300 years ago by Haleopotra Clan. The Halepotras and Meghwals of Hodka live in mud huts known as the Bhunga. Circular in shape, the Bhungas have thick walls built using Mati or clay, which keep the interiors cool during the summers and warm in the winters. The circular design, mud plaster, and thatched roof protect the walls of these huts from strong winds and seismic activity. The women use earth pigments to paint beautiful motifs on the interior and exterior of the Bhunga.

message: Situated 2 km from Bishnupur, #Jor Bangla is an elegant mud-bricked temple built by Raghunath Singha II in 1655 A.D. Bishnupur is renowned for its ancient Hindu terracotta temples and Jor Bangla is one among them. The temple is highly influenced by classical Bengali architecture and is designed as two hut-like structures with distinct angled roofs connected together by a tower at the crown. The magnificent terracotta carvings and sculptures, depicting scenes from the Mahabharata, Ramayana and Krishna-Leela, will leave you awestruck.

message: If you are a lover of children’s literature, Chougan should be a must-visit on your itinerary. Chougan is the village that inspired Rudyard Kipling to pen his famous work, ‘The Jungle book’. This scenic tribal settlement lies close to the famous Kanha National Park, on the edge of the beautiful River Narmada in #Madhya Pradesh. The village, home to the Baiga and Gond communities, has a vibrant heritage, art and culture. So,take a break from the hustle and bustle of city life and go tribal for a while.

data.message: Howrah railway station (HWH) in West Bengal, India is the largest railway station in all of South Asia by area! It daily handles the largest number of trains than any railway station in the Indian subcontinent! Having 23 platforms in all, the highest in South Asia, it possesses one of the most complex and massive route relay interlocking systems. Mail, Express, Passenger, MEMU, DEMU and Kolkata suburban railway commuter trains (EMU trains) throng the railway station very frequently. Passenger density, train density and track density is one if the highest in the country. The railway station is operated both by Eastern Railway (Howrah Division) and South Eastern Railway (Kharagpur Division) of Indian Railways, the 3rd largest passenger railway network in the world! The OHE of the railway station is fully AC electrified.

message: Howrah Railway Station is the oldest railway station and the largest railway complex in India. With 23 platforms, it is one of the busiest railway stations in the country in terms of passenger volume per day. The #Howrah railway station also has the distinction of being the railway station with the highest train-handling capacity.

message: Located at the centre of Auroville, the #Matrimandir (Temple of The Mother), is an edifice of great spiritual importance for practitioners of Integral yoga. Designed by Roger Anger, the project took around 37 years to be completed. A place for individual silent concentration, Matrimandir does not belong to any specific religion or sect. Matrimandir is an epitome of innovation and architectural excellence; it is designed as a massive sphere encapsulated by twelve petals. The golden discs in the dome reflect sunlight, giving the structure its radiance. The meditation hall or the inner chamber contains the largest optically-perfect glass globe in the world.

Narendra Modi, along with other dignitaries, inaugurated the Rashtrapati Bhavan Museum on 25 July 2016.  Spread over 10,000 sq. metres, it is the country’s only underground museum and features state-of the-art virtual reality exhibitions. The event coincided with the completion of the fourth year of Shri. Pranab Mukherjee's presidency. Built at a cost of Rs 80 crore and in 19 months, the museum showcases more than 2,000 artifacts that capture and recreate some of the significant moments in the history of India. The museum will open to the public on October 2.

Please book online at https://goo.gl/Vu8swZ to visit #RashtrapatiBhavan  #IncredibleIndia

message: A classical South Indian style of Painting, the Thanjavur painting originated in the town of #Thanjavur, Tamil Nadu. For making these paintings, the artists use gold foil, precious and semi­precious stones, pearls, glass pieces, and colourful paints. Mostly, the artworks portray the pictures of gods, goddesses, saints and various episodes from the Hindu Puranas. The Tanjore style requires a lot of effort and dedication, and people from across the world flock to India to learn this traditional art. #IncredibleIndia

message: Surrounded by pavilions, towers, arches and cupolas, Udaipur Palace or City Palace, is a fine blend of Rajasthani, Mughal, medieval, Chinese and European architecture. Built on the banks of the serene Pichola Lake, the palace complex comprises the Mubarak Mahal (the palace of reception) and the Maharani’s Palace (the palace of the queen). Mubarak Mahal is home to the Maharaja Sawai Man Singh II Museum and displays a unique and extensive collection of royal costumes, Pashmina silk, Benarasi silk saris, and others with Sanganeri prints and folk embroidery.

message: Located in Mehrauli, #NewDelhi, Qutub Minar is the tallest brick minaret in the world. A fine specimen of Indo-­Islamic style of architecture, the tower is around 73 metres high, with a diameter of around 14.3 metres. The tower has 379 steps from bottom to top, and the red sandstone walls are covered with highly intricate carvings and inscribed with verses from the holy Quran. A UNESCO listed site, the Qutub Minar is one of the most magnificent monuments in the world.

message: The Hemis festival is one of the most popular religious festivals of Ladakh. The annual festival is held in the courtyard of Hemis Gompa, believed to be the biggest and the wealthiest monastery in #Ladakh. It is celebrated in honour of the birth anniversary of Lord Padmasambhava, the founder of Tibetan Tantric Buddhism. In this colourful and vibrant two-­day pageant, the Lamas perform the fabulous mask dance accompanied by cymbals, drums, and long horns. A splendid fair, displaying handicrafts, is yet another highlight of the festival. Be a part of this cultural extravaganza and take home some lovely souvenirs for your near and dear.

message: Narali Purnima or Coconut Day is celebrated mainly by the fisherfolks in India. It signifies the end of monsoon season in Maharashtra and is celebrated on the full moon day of the month of Shravan. On this occasion, people offer coconuts to appease the God of Sea. It is believed that feasting on coconut will keep them safe from the wrath of the seas and would also bring an abundant catch of fish. Decorated boats and festoons add fervor to the day.

It's "its", not "it’s". ("...the city of Kolkata still retains it’s old-world legacy...")

"It's" means "it is"; "its" is the possessive form of "it".

Please correct it immediately. I can't believe that such a horrible mistake has been made on an official page of the government!
Unique Indian trams only in my city!

message: Very few cities in the world still have trams. In fact, with the advent of motor cars and bullet-speed bikes, the world has completely forgotten this mode of transport. However, the city of Kolkata still retains its old-world legacy. Trams are considered as one of the cheapest and healthiest modes of transportation in terms of zero-pollution. So, next time, if you are in #Kolkata, don’t miss out on a leisurely ride in a tram!

message:
Smihastha Kumbh Mela 2016 (Ujjain, Madhya Pradesh)

The Simhastha Kumbh is an unrivalled celebration in India. The most popular legend regarding the origin of Kumbh Melas is the Samudra Manthan or 'churning of the ocean'. Gods and demons competed ¬ercely in the churning in search of the divine nectar of immortality. During this epic battle to capture the Urn (Kumbh) containing the nectar, drops of the precious liquid fell on four places – Haridwar, Prayag (Allahabad), Nashik and Ujjain. Hence, river Kshipra became the enhancer of life and to celebrate this event since then the grand festival came in vogue. Kumbh Mela, is held once every twelve years at these four places and attracts millions of devotees.

Grand Simhastha, on the Ghats of the glorious Kshipra

The Ujjain Kumbh is celebrated when Jupiter ascends into sun sign Leo's quarter or the Simha constellation of zodiac, which is why it is called 'Simhastha'. The Simhastha is special in Ujjain as it is the seat of divine Mahakal - the Lord of all times. The ritual of bathing in the holy waters of Kshipra begins on the full moon day of the Hindu month of Chaitra (March-April) and continues on various dates until the full moon shows up in the following month of Vaishakha.

Simhastha 2016 will begin on 22nd of April and will continue till 21st of May.

Sadhus of various sects from across the country assemble in Ujjain and mingle with ordinary people as they take their ritual dip in the holy waters of the Kshipra.! For moreinfo log on to http://www.mptourism.com/pdf-html/simhastha/index-su.html  (Image and info courtesy MP Tourism)

message:
WELCOME TO AMRITSAR @spiritofindiarun
Inextricably linked with the history of Sikhism, Amritsar is amongst the most revered sites of the world. It was founded as recently as the 16th century. Its name is a derivative of the Amrit Sarovar (pool of nectar) amidst which stands the Golden Temple, the most sacred of Sikh shrines. Accounts suggest that Guru Amardas purchased the land from Emperor Akbar and decided to build a tank at the site. Following his death, it was completed by Guru Ramdas and also came to be known as Chak Ramdas or Guru ka Chak. Some of the oldest markets in Amritsar, notably Guru ka Bazaar, date back to his time. The construction of the Golden Temple was initiated by Guru Arjan Dev while Guru Hargobind, who accorded the religion a martial temper, built the Akal Takht in 1606. Amritsar has a rich history encompassing various mythical and historical narratives including the epic Ramayana. It is believed that the site called Ram Tirath was Maharish Valmiki’s ashram, where Sita reportedly gave birth to her twin sons, Luv and Kush. The Gobindgarh Fort and Ram Bagh were built by Maharaja Ranjit Singh, the founder of the Sikh Empire. While the Jallianwala Bagh continues to be the most evocative monument to India’s freedom struggle. The Khalsa College, established by visionary leaders at the beginning of the 20th century turned Amritsar into a hub of education. Also a centre of thriving industry since its inception, Amritsar is famed for its textiles, particularly shawls, and for its carpets. Amritsar has gained tremendous popularity for its gourmet traditions; especially the dhabas (roadside eatery) that churn out, amongst an inexhaustible list of delicacies, irresistible kulchas, chola-bhaturas, tandoori chicken and fried fish. Amritsar has all the makings of a well-rounded tourist destination; its ancient legends, historical monuments, places of worship, old bazaars, theatre traditions and colourful festivals all serve as a window to its robust past. Excursions to the Harike Bird Sanctuary and visits to the India-Pakistan border at Wagah are an absolute delight, while breaking bread or celebrating Diwali with the denizens of this hospitable city is without parallel.(Courtesy Punjab Tourism)

Kausani - Peace among thickly forested lanes and Himalayan views
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Located 53 km. to the north of Almora, Kausani, the brithplace of Hindi poet Sumitra Nandan Pant, is a picturesque hill station famous for its scenic splendour and its spectacular view of the Himalayas. Situated at 6075 feet above sea level, atop a narrow ridge, Kausani is thickly forested and separated from the soaring Nanda Devi ranges by low mountains. In 1929, Mahatma Gandhi stayed here at the Anasakti Ashram.

message:
Gulmarg - The Meadow Of Flowers
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Welcome to Gulmarg the hill resort with magical meadows and mountains. Then natural beauty of Gulmarg has attracted tourists since long. In fact the hill resort of Gulmarg literally means "the meadow of flowers". The snow-clad peaks and the lovely landscapes of Gulmarg have provided background for several Bollywood ventures.

The slopes of Gulmarg make it Asia’s only heli-skiing resort. There are immense beauty and adventure activities that make Gulmarg much more than a cool hill resort. British discovered the hill resort of Gulmarg in 1927 during their colonial rule in India. 
- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/gulmarg

message:
Dharamshala
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
The hillside town of Dharamshala, stretches along a spur of the Dhauladhar mountain range amidst magnificent deodar, conifer and pine forests, tea gardens and mist-soaked hills. Since 1960, when it became the temporary headquarters of the Dalai Lama, it has been attracting seekers of spiritual enlightenment from all over the world. 
The headquarters of the Kangra district, Dharamshala is divided into two distinct parts - Lower Dharamshala, and Upper Dharamshala with places like Mcleod Ganj and Forsyth Ganj, which are names that bear witness to the history of the area. The place is an excellent base for walks and treks into the Dhauladhar range. 
- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/dharamshala

High up near the Himalayas with Mt. Kanchenjunga as a backdrop, Darjeeling in the state of West Bengal, is worth a visit, where, ancient forests, quaint houses and friendly people make the trip to this most famous hill station of India worth it. The mystique of Darjeeling is glamorous thanks to its landscape. 
The toy train enables travellers to explore the wonderful hill station at a calm pace, soaking in the environs and culture of every part of destination that is Darjeeling. 
The place is famous honeymoon destination and trailhead for numerous treks as well as a great countryside ideal for adventure sport lovers.

message:
Dalhousie
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Located at an altitude of 1854.mts in the Chamba district of Himachal Pradesh, Dalhousie is one of India’s most well known holiday destinations. Named after Lord Dalhousie the British viceroy in India, this picturesque hill station, built around five hills, nestles in the outer slopes of the Dhauladhar range and attracts visitors who will be startled by its relaxed atmosphere, invigorating air, warm sunshine and quiet surroundings.
Here you will find some fine specimens of British colonial architecture. The unofficial honeymoon Mecca of India, Dalhousie is the reminiscent of an English town, with faded, elegant buildings evocative of another era. It is also becoming a haven for outdoor adventure activities, including trekking, cycling and rock climbing. 
- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/dalhousie

message:
Coonoor
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Coonoor it is the second largest hill station in the Nilgiris. It stands on a lower ridge of the plateau at an altitude of 1,858 m (6,100 ft), surrounded by verdant tea and coffee estates. 

This picturesque hill retreat is covered by grassy meadows, with a profusion of sunflowers, marigolds and rhododendrons, all growing wild. 

Coonoor’s weather remains pleasantly cool throughout the year and this together with its serene surrounding, makes it an ideal place for a peaceful break. 
- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/coonoor

message:
Chamba
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
There are many stunning, intriguing places around the world, but very few are as beautiful and awe-inspiring as Chamba. Located in the blossom of green mountains with perennial falls and streams, Chamba is one of those places that not only lives up to its image, but exceeds it. 
A travel to this place evokes many images... fairy-tale snow-capped mountain vistas, rushing torrent of the Ravi River and beautiful temples. One of the most famous hill stations in India that has been holding a magical allure for travellers, Chamba, a former princely state, is the administrative headquarters of the district of the same name.

"..But some elected politicians have already begun to grapple with their responsibility toward sexual minorities, and thanks to the parallel efforts of activists, a small but growing legislative agenda for queer rights has become evident. A new bill protecting the rights of transgenders has passed in the upper house of Parliament and will be presented in the lower house this year. Last January, Madhu Bai Kinnar was elected mayor of Raigarh — the first transgender elected to run any Indian city.

Unlike in the United States, where L.G.B.T. rights are an issue too hot for many politicians to touch, in India homophobia is diffuse, and hardly features in our culture wars. And so the prospect grows brighter that Section 377 will eventually be changed through legislation — through a process that appeals not just to India’s Constitution, but to its society as well."

message:
Yelagiri - Serenity and scenic splendour in the hills
--------------------------------------------------------------------

Yelagiri Hill, a popular hill station located 1,048.5 m above sea level, is situated amidst four mountains in a serene and scenic ambience; it is well known for its salubrious climate all year around. Getting to Yelagiri hilltop, you will traverse 14 hairpin bends, each of which offers a panoramic, breathtaking view of the hills and their surroundings. The seventh bend is significant, since it offer the view of the slopes of the mountain and the green forests that carpet the hill. Yelagiri is located amidst tribal villages, and the villagers’ customs, habits, and houses are unique. Yelagiri offers many exceptional opportunities for trekking and para-gliding. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/yelagiri

message:
Junagadh
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

Located at the base of spectacular Girnar Hills, Junagadh, headquarters of the district of the same name, is an ancient fortified city, rich in myth and legend. A princely state in British India, the place is named after the ‘Old Fort’ which encircled the old city.
The presence of 14 Rock Edicts of the Mauryan Emperor Ashoka cut into a big rock outside the city bears testimony to its antiquity and attracts the historically minded. One of the reasons for visiting Junagadh is to transit to Sasangir, the entrancing preserve of Asiatic lion or to tour the beautiful shrine of Somnath. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/junagadh

message:
Kalimpong - Colonial Charm in Mountains

Kalimpong has for long been in the shadows of its better known big brother – Darjeeling. Situated between the Deolo and Durbindra Hills at the foot of the mighty Himalayas, the landscape of this famous hill station in the state of West Bengal is a feast for one's eyes. 

51 km east of Darjeeling and at an altitude of 1250 metres, Kalimpong is a blaze of colour throughout the year thanks to the richness of its breathtaking flora. Apart from being a place to head to escape the heat of the plains, Kalimpong is the reminiscent of an English town, with faded, elegant buildings evocative of another era. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/kalimpong

message:
Jog Falls - Feast from Nature
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Witness nature’s headlong tumble, as the Sharavati River makes a spectacular drop of 956 ft in four distinct cascades – known locally as Raja, Rani, Roarer and Rocket – to create the fifth highest falls in Asia. One of India’s greatest scenic wonders, the Jog Falls is at their exuberant best during the monsoon, with arching rainbows colouring the mist. 

When the sluice gates of the upstream Linganamakki Dam are closed, taking a walk right down to the bottom of the gorge is a once-in-a-lifetime experience. A large hydro electric power plant is located down stream here. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/jog-falls

message:
Gokarna - Spirituality and Beauty Combined
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Literally meaning ‘cow’s ear,’ the quant town of Gokarna in Uttara Kannada district of Karnataka is formed by the ear-shaped confluence of two rivers and the favourite haunt of Hindu pilgrims, Sanskrit scholars, and beach buffs. Om Beach, one of Gokarna’s five famed beaches, takes the shape of an “Om”, a Hindu spiritual symbol.

The other beaches, wedged between gigantic cliffs that protrude like delicate fingers into the sea, are Gokarna, Kudle, Half Moon, and Paradise. The drive up the winding path that leads to Gokarna is a scenic delight with rocky mountains and the Western Ghats on one side, and the Arabian Sea on the other. Adventurous tourists must be prepared for a bit of cliff-scrambling in this coastal town. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/gokarna

message:
Bodhgaya - Buddhism’s most sacred and significant site
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

Bodhgaya, the most important site of Buddhist pilgrimage in the world, is situated in the state of Bihar. 
The place is a sacred site of the first order, and its central temple, the UNESCO World Heritage listed Mahabodhi Temple, is an obligatory stop on the Buddhist pilgrimage circuit. 
Adjacent to the Mahabodhi Temple is the Bodhi tree itself under which Prince Siddhartha Gautama is said to have attained Enlightenment 2,500 years ago. As a result he became the Buddha - the Enlightened One. Bodh Gaya or Uruvela, as it was known during Buddha’s times, is also a major pilgrimage centre for Hindus as Buddha is considered to be the ninth incarnation of Vishnu. 
- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/bodhgaya

message:
Jodhpur - A romantic journey into the past
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Located almost on the edge of the Thar Desert, the city of Jodhpur was founded in 1459 by Rao Jodha, the chief of the Rathore clan of Rajputs and was the capital of the State of Marwar. 

Jodhpur is also known as the Sun City because the sun shines brightly here every day of the year, and as Blue City since most houses in the old part of the city are painted blue.
 
The forts and palaces, temples and havelis, culture and tradition, spices and fabrics, colour and texture, a booming handicrafts industry, all add up to make this historic city worth a visit. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/jodhpur

message:
Varkala - Breathtaking destination not to be missed
------------------------------------------------------------------------

A famous beach destination in southern Kerala, Varkala comes lauded as a sacred pilgrimage center too. Like the white cliffs of Dover, the pink  cliffs at the Varkala Beach offer sensational view of the Arabian Sea. Mineral water springs originating from the cliff is believed to possess medicinal properties. 

A dip in the holy waters at the beach is believed to purge the body of impurities and the soul of all sins; hence the name 'Papanasam beach'. The place is home to 2000-year-old Vishnu Shrine of Janardhanaswamy. The Sivagiri Mutt established by the great social reformer, Sree Narayana Guru is another start attraction of the place. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/varkala

message:
Amritsar - Seat of Sikh faith, history and culture
----------------------------------------------------------------------

Amritsar, literally a Pool of Nectar, derives its name from Amrit Sarovar, the holy tank that surrounds the splendid Golden Temple. Guru Ramdas, the fourth Guru of the Sikh faith, founded Amritsar in 1579. He constructed a pool on land gifted by the Mughal Emperor Akbar and called it Amritsar. 

Home to the world famous Golden Temple, the 400-year-old city of Amritsar is the most important seat of Sikh history and culture. 

One of the most poignant memorials of free India -- Jallianwala Bagh – is also located in the city. Amritsar district was once a part of the vast area covered by the Indus valley Civilisation during the early period of history. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/amritsar

message:
Khajuraho - Eternal Expressions of Love

The temples of Khajuraho are India's unique gift to the world, representing, as they do, a paean to life, to love, to joy, perfect in execution and sublime in expression. Life, in every form and mood, has been captured in stone, testifying not only to the craftsman's artistry but also to the extraordinary breadth of vision of the Chandela Rajputs under whose rule the temples were conceived and constructed. The Khajuraho temples were built in the short span of a hundred years, from 950-1050 AD in truly inspired burst of creativity. Of the 85 original temples, 22 have survived till today to constitute one of the world's great artistic wonders. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/khajuraho

Dharamshala - The hillside town of Dharamshala, stretches along a spur of the Dhauladhar mountain range amidst magnificent deodar, conifer and pine forests, tea gardens and mist-soaked hills. Since 1960, when it became the temporary headquarters of the Dalai Lama, it has been attracting seekers of spiritual enlightenment from all over the world. 

The headquarters of the Kangra district, Dharamshala is divided into two distinct parts - Lower Dharamshala, and Upper Dharamshala with places like Mcleod Ganj and Forsyth Ganj, which are names that bear witness to the history of the area. The place is an excellent base for walks and treks into the Dhauladhar range.

Courtrallam is as small, charming town situated at an elevation of about 167 m on the Western Ghats in Tirunelveli district. 

The waterfalls for which Courtrallam is famous, are formed by a sharp three stage drop of about 91 m (300 ft) by the Chittar river. Several other seasonal and a few perennial rivers such as the Manimuthar River, the Pachaiyar River and the Tambaraparani River originate in this region. 

A large number of tourists come here mainly to bath in the falls which are believed to have medicinal properties which has earned Courtrallam the title of the Spa of the South.

message:
Cuttack - History and nature blend into a rich, seamless harmony

Cuttack is Orissa’s oldest city and was established in 989 AD. A relaxed and laid-back city, Cuttack is today mainly a farmer and trader town, offering a refreshing array of landscapes, activities and characters, and whether one is city-lover keen on shopping, a history or archaeology enthusiast, a religious person, there is something on offer for everyone. 

Steeped in history, Barabati Fort is one of the principal visitor attractions in Orissa.

The fort casts its historical shadow against the natural surroundings, and both history and nature blend into a rich, seamless harmony.

Bandhavgarh
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Bandhavgarh National Park, lying in the heart of the Vindhya Mountain Range in Central India, is a small and compact National Park, yet full of game. The density of the tiger population at Bandhavgarh is the highest known in India. 
The centre of the park is dominated by the majestic Bandhavgarh Fort built in the 14th century, around which are numerous caves containing shrines and ancient Sanskrit inscriptions. The park has four main entrances, Panpatha in the north, Tala in the east (most of the hotels are located in Tala), Dhamokar in the south-west and Khitauli in the west. Two roads, Umaria-Rewa highway and Parasi-Katni road via Khitauli pass through the park. Tala is a small village on the Umaria-Rewa state highway. 

The Original home of all the white tigers alive, today, Bandhavgarh was the hunting ground of the Maharajas of Rewa; their old fort still dominates a hill in the forest. These white tigers were found in the old state of Rewa for many years. The last known tiger was captured by Maharaja Martand Singh in 1951. The White Tiger, Mohan, is now stuffed and on display in the palace of the Maharaja of Rewa. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/bandhavgarh

Alappuzha - Venice of the East
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This laid-back market town Alappuzha, previously known as Alleppy, is built on canals that form a web, which serves the coir industry. All around are coconut palms, and obviously, coir making, boat building, toddy tapping and fish farming are mainstays of the village economy. 

Every August, Alappuzha comes to life with an adrenaline-pumping event that sees huge, low slung chundan vellams (snake boats), rowed by up to 100 people, compete for the Nehru Cup. Alappuzha's attraction does not, however, lie solely in its natural aspects. Apaprt from the Poomkavu Church, other well-known religious sites in and around Alappuzha are Mullackal Raja Rajeshwari Temple, Mannarasala Temple and Salafi Juma Masjid Mosque.

message:
Amritsar - Seat of Sikh faith, history and culture
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Amritsar, literally a Pool of Nectar, derives its name from Amrit Sarovar, the holy tank that surrounds the splendid Golden Temple. Guru Ramdas, the fourth Guru of the Sikh faith, founded Amritsar in 1579. He constructed a pool on land gifted by the Mughal Emperor Akbar and called it Amritsar. 

Home to the world famous Golden Temple, the 400-year-old city of Amritsar is the most important seat of Sikh history and culture. 

One of the most poignant memorials of free India -- Jallianwala Bagh – is also located in the city. Amritsar district was once a part of the vast area covered by the Indus valley Civilisation during the early period of history.

message:
Bijapur - Heritage monuments of exceptional beauty
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The foundations of this historic city were laid during the reign of the Chalukyan Dynasty. They called it 'Vijayapura' or the 'City of Victory' from where comes its present name Bijapur.

This one-time capital of the Adil Shahi kings (1489-1686) is dotted with mosques, mausoleums, palaces, fortifications, watchtowers, and strong gateways, with the massive Gol Gumbaz, the world’s second largest dome, dominating the landscape for miles around. 

Bijapur experienced a great burst of architectural activity under the Adil Shahi rulers. It is also famous for the hand-made sarees of llkal. Bijapur is also the best base from which to see other exceptional heritage sites such as Aihole, Badami and Pattadakal.

message:
Pithoragarh - Abundant natural beauty and stunning snowy view
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The easternmost hill district of Uttarakhand, Pithoragarh and its surroundings are known for their abundant natural beauty. Nestling in a small valley, barely 5 km long and 2 km wide, the town was an important landmark during the reign of the Chand Rajas of Kumaon. 

Pithoragarh is the district headquarters and its government buildings are housed in the hill fort of Pithoragarh at a distance of 7 km from the main town. From the Chandak hill located here, one gets a panoramic view of snowy ranges extending from the Trishul-Nanda Devi, Panchchuli Group to Mount Appi of Nepal. 

- See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/pithoragarh

message:
Bikaner
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Founded in 1488 by Rao Bikaji, Bikaner is situated on an elevated ground, surrounded by a 7 km long fortified wall with five entrance gates. 

A magnificent fort built between 1588 and 1593 dominates the city. The fort and palace are built in the red sandstone that characterises Bikaner. 

The city is also known for its intricately carved Jharokas, stone screens found on the windows of the Junagarh fort, temples and havelis. Bikaner was and is the centre for Usta Art, a generic term for the Manoti-Naqqashi (embossed and unembossed floral and geometric patterned objects layered with gold) media produced by Usta family master artistans of Bikaner. 

One of the best known exports of the city is Bikaneri Bhujia, a spicy snack made from moth dal, spices and edible oil. Asia's large camel farm is located here. 

See more at: http://incredibleindia.org/index.php/travel/destination/bikaner

Gwalior
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Legend has it that Gwalior was founded in 8th century AD by a chieftain known as Suraj Sen or Surya Sen of Kachwaha Rajput clan who,when struck by a deadly disease, was curd by a hermit-saint Gwalipa. As a mark of respect to the saint, he built the city of Gwalior after the name of the saint.

message:
Omkareshwar

A pilgrimage place of top order for Hindus, Omkareshwar is a highlight of any trip to the state of Madhya Pradesh. Located on the island of Mandhata or Shivapuri formed by the Narmada river, shaped like the holiest of all Hindu symbols, 'Om', the sacred shrine has always been the focal point of devotion and spiritual yearnings for Hindus for thousands of years. 

Omkareshwar is one of the Dwadasa Jyotirlinga shrines or the 12 shrines enshrining Shiva in the form of a Jyotirlingam in the country. Built in the Nagara style, the Omkareshwar temple is characterized by a lofty shikhara. You can also find here shrines dedicated to Annapurna and Ganesha.

message:
Orchha - Medieval Legacy in Stone

Orchha’s grandeur has been captured in stone, frozen in time; a rich legacy to the ages. For, on the medieval city, the hand of time has rested lightly and the p alaces and temples built by its Bundela rulers in the 16th and 17th centuries retain much of their pristine perfection.

Orchha was founded in the 16th century by the Bundela Rajput chieftain, Rudra Pratap, who chose this stretch of land along the Betwa river as an ideal site for his capital. Of the succeeding rulers, the most notable was Raja Bir Singh Ju Deo who built the exquisite Jehangir Mahal, a tiered palace crowned by graceful chhatris. From here the view of soaring temple spires and cenotaphs is spectacular.

Complementing the noble proportions of their exteriors are interiors which represent the finest flowering of the Bundela school of painting. In the Laxminarayan Temple and Raj Mahal, vibrant murals encompassing a variety of religious and secular themes, bring the walls and ceilings to rich life. Strewn around the area are the little shrines and memorials, each with its own poignant history, each contributing to the nostalgic beauty that is Orchha.

- See more at: http://www.incredibleindia.org/en/travel/destination/orchha

message:
Sanchi - Masterpieces of Buddhist Art

Sanchi’s stupas, monasteries, temples and pillars dating from the 3rd century BC to the 12th century AD have been declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO. The most famous of these monuments, Stupa 1, known as the Great Stupa, was originally built by the Mauryan Emperor Ashoka, the then governor of Ujjayini, whose wife Devi was the daughter of a merchant from the adjacent town of Vidisha. Their son Mahindra and daughter Sanghamitra were born in Ujjayini and sent to Sri Lanka, where they converted to king, the queen and their people to Buddhism.

The Sanchi hill goes up in shelves with Stupa 2 situated on a lower shelf, Stupa 1, Stupa 3, the 5th century Gupta Temple No.17 and the 7th century temple No. 18 are on the intermediate shelf and a later monastery is on the crowning shelf. The balustrade surrounding Stupa 2, carved with aniconic representations of the Buddha, was added in the late 2nd century BC under the Satavahanas.

The adjacent Gupta temple no.17 was hailed by Sir John Marshall as one of the most rationally organized structures in Indian architecture. Though small, it was a herald of all the principles which went into the engineering of an Indian temple in the early medieval period. The Buddhas in the perambulatory surrounding Stupa 1 are not contemporary with the Stupa but belong to the Gupta period in the mid-5th century AD. The monastery and the temple with the tall pillars adjacent to Stupa 1 and the temple near the monastery on the crowning shelf illustrate the evolution of the architectural form after the 5th century Gupta temple. 

- See more at: http://www.incredibleindia.org/en/travel/destination/sanchi

We made an online booking of two rooms for two nights in KSTDC Hotel Mayura Pine Top at Nandi Hills on 26.06.2015 and 27.06.2015. We stay at Kolkata. My son works in Bangalore. We went to Bangalore for two weeks. So, we hoped that we would enjoy a quite stay for two nights in this place, as it was very close to Bangalore, only 60 kms away. 
Nandi Hills is about 4500 ft high. Hotel Pine Top is situated in a beautiful place on the hill top in an isolated place. We reached the hotel at about 17 hrs in the dusk of 26.06.2015, by climbing a serpentine hilly road and became exited to enjoy the coming nights. 
When we arrived at the reception desk of Hotel Pine Top, we found that there were some hotel personnel seated near the entrance and some guests were enjoying evening tea and snacks in adjacent dining room. On the way, we also noticed a lot of parked cars, as it was Friday, the beginning of a weekend. 
We informed the hotel personnel that we had room bookings. They advised us to wait, but none came forward. After a while, one person moved to us. We told him that we had prior booking and showed him the reservation voucher. He called another person, who took our luggage, guided us to downstairs and opened two rooms. Rooms were two stories below the reception and one would have to climb down by the stairs by the side of the building. It was drizzling and the sky was extremely cloudy.
The rooms were glass-fitted with open front view of the valley. The view was really superb. There were steps to go down to a garden. From there, vast valley was being seen. The place was really calm and quite. There was a half-circle view-point in the complex, in the same level of reception, from where the view was more wide open.
But we could not stay. When we reached the reception, we found that everyone was disliking our presence. No one greeted us, as if we were non-invitees. No one was coming forward to speak with us. The person, who moved to us informed that there was no room available. No welcome message. Later we found that there was no other boarder beside us. When we informed that we had prior reservation, he told with a stoned face that there was shortage of water and electricity, as it was a hilly area. Might be. Then came the next point. We would have to take dinner within 7 PM, as there would no electricity after 7 PM. Water would be not available after 7 PM, 
We, however, accepted the proposal as we had nothing to do and nowhere to go. But, when the rooms were opened for us, no electricity was present in the rooms. Then we found no water in the tap in the bathrooms with lots of cockroaches in the rooms and bathrooms. Rooms were not clean and linens were not fresh and at some places dirty. It was becoming dark and we were horrified to find that big rats were moving freely inside the rooms and bathrooms. Street dogs were freely circling in the corridor and garden. We also came to know that mobile network would not work there. We were puzzled to think what to do in that evening. However, we decided not to stay in that horrible place. There was also no telephone connection between the rooms and the reception upstairs. So, at night, if there would be any emergency, we would find our way through rodents and dogs to go to reception upstairs, might be no one would be available there. After a good thought, we did not take any risk to stay there. Luckily, Bangalore was not far away.
We came back to the reception with our luggage and asked for the complaint book. When we told the hotel personnel that we would not stay, none asked us the reason, as if it was a better decision. We also noticed that in the complaint register, there were similar complaints by the previous boarders/customers, but KSTDC took no step. We wrote our grievances in the complaint register, but till date, no official from KSTDC/Karnataka Government telephoned us or made any query. We understood that though we noticed a lot of cars, all those people would return back to Bangalore in the evening and none would stay there at night. But we came from Kolkata,a far away place, to enjoy and were cheated. Probably, KSTDC/Karnataka Government does not have time to bother in such petty matter.
On our way back to Bangalore, we found other nearby hotels/resorts/lodges with electricity arrangements. We toured to other hilly remote places, even in high altitude, where supply of power were arranged at least upto 9/10 pm. Nandi Hills is a very good place for 1-2 nights stay, as it is very near to Bangalore. We could not understand why Karnataka Government was not developing the place. The hotel is beautifully placed, rooms are not bad, a big restaurant is attached, approachable road is there and lots of tourists come to this place. Only some developments, like electricity, water and mobile tower, are to be made. Then many other hoteliers will be interested to come to this place and the place will turn into a hot tourist spot. It is a good business opportunity for the local Government and also an avenue for development of local people. Instead of improving the place, KSTDC is charging higher for the weekends. The tariff of a double-bedded room was Rs.1150 in normal weekdays, whereas in the weekend it would jump to Rs.1500, which we had to pay in full. We felt very sorry that we could not enjoy this beautiful place. State Government is turning a deaf ear to the complaints made by the past boarders/customers, as the hotel personnel should inform the authorities that we left the hotel without staying. It was a case of cheating in the part of Karnataka Government. It is known to common people like us that the hotels/lodges run by Government/state bodies are safer and better places than the private ones.
We hope that Karnataka Government/KSTDC should be ashamed for charging boarders/customers without giving any normal basic amenities and should make booking after developing the hotel and area.

http://www.tripadvisor.in/ShowUserReviews-g2289003-d3428129-r306536195-Hotel_Mayura_Pine_Top_Nandi_Hills-Nandigunda_Karnataka.html#

message:
Allahabad - The Kumbh-City

A city of many dimensions is what befits a description of Allahabad. In addition to being a major pilgrimage centre, the city has played an important part in the formation of modern India. Hindu mythology states that Lord Brahma, the creator god, chose a land for 'Prakrishta Yajna'. This land, at the confluence of three holy rivers - Ganga, Yamuna and Saraswati, blessed by gods, came to be known as 'Prayag' or 'Allahabad'. 

Foreseeing the sanctity of the place, Lord Brahma also called it as 'Tirth Raj' or 'King of all pilgrimage centers’.' The Scriptures - Vedas and the great epics - Ramayana and Mahabharata, refer to this place as Prayag.

Centuries followed. Allahabad became the headquarters of North Western Provinces, after being shifted from Agra. Well preserved relics of the British impact include the Muir College and the All Saints Cathedral. 

Many important events in India's struggle for freedom, took place here - the emergence of the first Indian National Congress in 1885, the beginning of Mahatma Gandhi's non-violence movement in 1920. 

- See more at: http://www.incredibleindia.org/travel/destination/allahabad
